@realmoney The Post Mortem * The consensus believe that an easy Fed is market friendly * I disagree with the consensus as the core of valuation is profit and economic growth both of which will likely miss The markets lost all of their Post Fed ramp in the last hour of trading

As posted, I aggressively shorted into the strength. In watching the business news and listening to the commentary I was surprised that there was not one single naysayer after the Powell press conference.

Everyone was bullish on the basis that interest rates will be lower for longer. I will remind you that in my 15 Surprises for 2019 realmoney.thestreet.com/doug… I was using a 2.25% target on the ten year US note's yield and expected more easing to be announced in this year's second

half. I am not changing my tunes. And these tunes, to this observor, is not a positive one - the essence of which is disappointing profits and growth relative to consensus expectations. Low interest rates, that we have experienced for years are always - in every cycle -

a source of "mischief" and a misallocation of resources. I suppose the lessons of 1999 and 2007 have already been lost by many. The unanimity of bullish commentary may be an ominous sign for the markets- and so might the 20 handle reversal of the S&P in the last sixty minutes

as well as the newly founded tilt towards "growthy" stocks in a world without much growth. (It just seems too pat). While I am never as confident as most, I expect that a reassessment of slowing global economic and profit growth will pressure equities over the next few weeks and

months. Color me more Bearish and not less Bearish after Powell and Co. abrogated their responsibilities and have threatened our economic futures. @cnbcfastmoney Beware of the established consensus above.

Cory Booker Finds His Moment nyti.ms/2Wap60I David Brooks with a beautiful column about Cory Booker: Three emotions run through Booker’s campaign. The first is an unabashed patriotism, and with it the conviction that despite our differences, Americans are still connected

by sacred bonds. “Patriotism is love of country, and you cannot love your country unless you love your fellow countrymen and women,” he told an Iowa audience last month. Republican or Democrat — we are brothers and sisters under the skin. The second is the dogged but radical

hopefulness that he inherited from the black church. Booker uses religious categories more naturally than any other candidate: grace, faith, sacrificial love, the command to love your neighbor as yourself, the awareness that love has a redemptive power to cast out fear.

The gospels are pretty clear that the correct response to hate is love. “Love means that I see you, I see your worth, I see your dignity,” Booker said at that rally last month. “Your destiny is my destiny.”

The third emotion is simple gratitude. Booker had to overcome challenges in life, and he has seen many more, but his family story is a success story. The church raised money for his grandmother to go to school. His parents worked at IBM. He was elected class president in

high school before going off to Stanford and Yale Law. Others see America’s institutions as systems of oppression, but Booker calls the founders “imperfect geniuses.” America needs reform, but our inheritance is a precious one.

When you’re in the midst of everyday life, the idea that you can deal with one group or another only through condemnation and attack is absurd. You don’t build a better society by turning yourself into a rotten human being.
